  <subsection xml:id="problems-reparametrization">
    <title>Reparametrization</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider a general parametric curve (in either <m>\RR^2</m>
          or <m>\RR^3</m>)  <m>\gamma(t)</m> with <m>t \in
          [0,\infty)</m>. For each of these substitutions, describe
          how the reparametrization changes the movement along the
          curve and the domain of the parameter.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <m>t = 3s</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>t = \frac{s}{4}</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>t = s + 7</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>t = s - 10</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>t = s^2</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>t = \sqrt{s}</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>t = e^s</m>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>t = -s</m>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <m>t = 3s</m>
              <p>
                The movement will be consistently three times faster.
                For any value of <m>s</m>, the position based on the
                original parameter would be three times further along
                the curve, so we move through the curve three times as
                fast. 
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>t = \frac{s}{4}</m>
              <p>
                The movement will be one quarter th eoriginal speed.
                For any value of <m>s</m>, the position based on the
                original parameter would be only one quarter as far
                along the curve, so we move through the curve at one
                quarter the original speed.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>t = s + 7</m>
              <p>
                The speed doesn't change. However, at <m>s=0</m> (the
                starting time for the new variable), we are already
                along the curve at <m>t=7</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>t = s - 10</m>
              <p>
                The speed doesn't change. However, at <m>s=0</m> (the
                starting time for the new variable), we have moved
                back along the curve to <m>t = -10</m>. If <m>t</m>
                doesn't take negative values, then we would have to
                start the new variable at <m>s = 10</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>t = s^2</m>
              <p>
                By squaring the new variable, we will be going faster
                and faster compared with the old variable. Moving
                linearly in <m>s</m> is moving quadratically in
                <m>t</m>, getting faster and faster.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>t = \sqrt{s}</m>
              <p>
                By taking the square rook we will be going slower and
                slower compared with the old variable. Moving linearly
                in <m>s</m> is moving only <m>\sqrt{s}</m> in
                <m>t</m>, getting slower and slower.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>t = e^s</m>
              <p>
                As we move on in the new variable, the speed will
                accelerate more and more compared with the old
                variable. This is like the quadratic change, but more
                dramatic, since the exponential function grows faster.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <m>t = -s</m>
              <p>
                The speed will not change, but the direction of
                movement along the curve will be reversed. 
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="problems-arclength">
    <title>Arclength</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the arclength of this parametric curve.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp \gamma(t) = (t, 3t-6) \amp \amp t \in [0,7]
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I calculate the derivatives of the two coordinates.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp x^{\prime}(t) = 1
              \amp \amp y^\prime(t) = 3
            </mrow>
          </md>
          I then put the into a pythagorian combination.
          <me>
            \sqrt{1^2 + 3^2} = \sqrt{10}
          </me>
          For arclength, I need to integrate this expression over the
          length of the curve.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \int_0^7 \sqrt{10} dt \amp = 7\sqrt{10}  
            </mrow>
          </md>
          The result of this integral is the arclength of the
          curve. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the arclength of this parametric curve.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp \gamma(t) = (t^2, 1-t^2) \amp \amp t \in [0,4]
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I calculate the derivatives of the two coordinates.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp x^{\prime}(t) = 2t 
              \amp \amp y^\prime(t) = -2t 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          I then put these into a pythagorian combination.
          <me>
            \sqrt{(2t)^2 + (-2t)^2} = \sqrt{8t^2} = (2\sqrt{2})t
          </me>
          For arclength, I need to integrate this expression over the
          length of the curve.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \int_0^4 (2\sqrt{2}) t \amp = (2\sqrt{2}) \frac{t^2}{2}
              \Big|_0^4 = (2\sqrt{2}) \frac{16}{2} = 16 \sqrt{2} 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          The result of this integral is the arclength of the
          curve. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the arclength of this parametric curve.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp \gamma(t) = (4\cos(t^2),4\sin(t^2)) \amp \amp t \in
              [0,\sqrt{2\pi}]
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I calculate the derivatives of the two coordinates.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp x^{\prime}(t) = -8t\sin (t^2) 
              \amp \amp y^\prime(t) = 8t \cos (t^2) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          I then put these into a pythagorian combination.
          <me>
            \sqrt{64 \sin^2 (t^2) + 64 \cos^2 (t^2)} = \sqrt{64} = 8 
          </me>
          For arclength, I need to integrate this expression over the
          length of the curve.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \int_0^{\sqrt{2\pi}} 8 \amp = 8 \sqrt{2\pi} 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          The result of this integral is the arclength of the
          function. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          This is a multi-part question on a historically important
          arclength calculation. (Some historical context is given
          and the end of the solution). 
          <ol>
            <li>
              Find a parametric curve which descrives an ellipse with
              semimajor axis <m>a</m> and semiminor axis <m>b</m>.
              (Its easiest to orient the larger ellipse axis along the
              <m>x</m> axis.
            </li>
            <li>
              Set up the arclength calculation to find the
              circumference of the ellipse.
            </li>
            <li>
              Factor <m>a</m> out of the square root and subtract a
              cosine term to that you can simplify using <m>(\sin^2 t
              + \cos^2 t = 1)</m>.
            </li>
            <li>
              We can define the eccentricity of the ellipse as <m>e =
              \sqrt{1 - \frac{b^2}{a^2}}</m>. Manipulate the integral
              so that <m>e</m> shows up under the square root, but
              <m>a</m> amd <m>b</m> are no longer under the square
              root.
            </li>
            <li>
               Calculate the integral in the special case <m>e=0</m>.
               (Since this happens only when <m>a=b</m>, this is a
               circle with radius <m>a</m>; you should recover the
               familiar circumference of a circle).
            </li>
            <li>
              Try to solve the integral for general eccentricity <m>0
              \lt e \lt 1</m>. Comment on the problems and barriers to
              integration.
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Find a parametric curve which descrives an ellipse with
                semimajor axis <m>a</m> and semiminor axis <m>b</m>.
                (It's easiest to orient the larger ellipse axis along the
                <m>x</m> axis.
              </p>
              <p>
                I can take the standard curve for the circle and just
                scale the amplitude of the two coordinate functions.
                <me>
                  \gamma(t) = (a \cos t, b \sin t) 
                </me>
                The shape is given by one period of the sine and
                cosine functions, so <m>t \in [0,2\pi]</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Set up the arclength calculation to find the
                circumference of the ellipse.
              </p>
              <p>
                The derivatives are <m>x^\prime = -a \sin t</m> and
                <m>y^\prime = b \cos t</m>. I put these in a
                pythagorian combination and integrate to find the
                arclength.
                <me>
                  \int_0^{2\pi} \sqrt{a^2 \sin^2 (t) + b^2 \cos^2
                  (t)} dt
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Factor <m>a</m> out of the square root and subtract a
                cosine term to that you can simplify using <m>(\sin^2 t
                + \cos^2 t = 1)</m>.
              </p>
              <md>
                <mrow>
                  \amp \int_0^{2\pi} \sqrt{a^2 \sin^2 (t) + b^2
                  \cos^2 (t)} dt
                </mrow>
                <mrow>
                  \amp = \int_0^{2\pi} \sqrt{a^2 \left( \sin^2 (t) +
                  \frac{b^2}{a^2} \cos^2 (t)\right)} dt
                </mrow>
                <mrow>
                  \amp = \int_0^{2\pi} a \sqrt{ \sin^2 (t) +
                  \frac{b^2}{a^2} \cos^2 (t)} dt
                </mrow>
                <mrow>
                  \amp = \int_0^{2\pi} a \sqrt{ \sin^2 (t) +
                  \cos^2 t + \left( \frac{b^2}{a^2} - 1 \right) \cos^2
                  (t)} dt
                </mrow>
                <mrow>
                  \amp = \int_0^{2\pi} a \sqrt{ 1 + \left(
                  \frac{b^2}{a^2} - 1 \right) \cos^2 (t)} dt
                </mrow>
              </md>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                We can define the eccentricity of the ellipse as <m>e =
                \sqrt{1 - \frac{b^2}{a^2}}</m>. Manipulate the integral
                so that <m>e</m> shows up under the square root, but
                <m>a</m> amd <m>b</m> are no longer under the square
                root.
              </p>
              <md>
                <mrow>
                  \int_0^{2\pi} a \sqrt{ 1 + \left(
                  \frac{b^2}{a^2} - 1 \right) \cos^2 (t)} dt
                </mrow>
                <mrow>
                  \int_0^{2\pi} a \sqrt{ 1 - \left(
                  1 - \frac{b^2}{a^2} \right) \cos^2 (t)} dt
                </mrow>
                <mrow>
                  = \int_0^{2\pi} a \sqrt{ 1 - e \cos^2 (t)} dt
                </mrow>
              </md>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                 Calculate the integral in the special case <m>e=0</m>.
                 (Since this happens only when <m>a=b</m>, this is a
                 circle with radius <m>a</m>; you should recover the
                 familiar circumference of a circle).
               </p>
               <me>
                  = \int_0^{2\pi} a \sqrt{ 1 - 0 \cos^2 (t)} dt = 
                  \int_0^{2\pi} a dt = 2\pi a
               </me>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Try to solve the integral for general eccentricity <m>0
                \lt e \lt 1</m>. Comment on the problems and barriers to
                integration.
              </p>
              <p>
                This is an impossible integral to solve with the
                method we are familiar with in this course. Without
                <m>e=0</m>, we can't make use of a trig identity to
                remove all the trig functions. We are left with this
                annoying <m>\cos^2 t</m> function inside the integral.
                No substitution works, since there are no trig
                functions outside the integral. 
              </p>
              <p>
                This is called an elliptic integral (of the second
                kind, technically). It was a major motivator in 19th
                century mathematics, since the circumference of the
                ellipse was considered an important geometric problem.
                It led, indirectly, to the objects known as elliptic
                curves. These are very important geometric object
                which seem strangely named, since they don't look like
                they have anything to do with ellipses. The connection
                if these integrals. Elliptic curves were invented as
                part of some clever and complicated new methods to
                approach ellitpic integrals.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="problems-parametrization-by-arclength">
    <title>Parametrization by Arclength</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Parametrize this curve by arclength.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp \gamma(t) = (t^2 \cos t, t^2 \sin t) \amp \amp t
              \in [0, \infty) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          First, I calculate the derivatives of the coordinate
          functions.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp x^\prime = -2t \sin t - t^2 \sin t 
              \amp \amp y^\prime = 2t \cos t + t^2 \cos t 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Then I calculate the pythagorian combination of these. This
          is a pretty long calculation, but I will be able to make use
          of a number of trig identities to simplify the terms inside
          the square root, and some terms cancel. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp \sqrt{4t^2 \cos^2 t - 4t^3 \cos t \sin t + t^2 \sin^2
              t + 4t^2 \sin^2 t + 4t^3 \cos t \sin t + t^4 \cos^2 t}
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \sqrt{4t^2 (\cos^2 t + \sin^2 t) + t^4 (\cos^2 t
              + \sin^2 t} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \sqrt{4t^2 + t^4} = t \sqrt{4+t^2}
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Then I set up the arclength function, which is the integral
          of this pythagorian combination.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              s(t) \amp = \int_0^t u \sqrt{4 + u^2} du 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          I can use a substitution here.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              v \amp = 4 + u^2 \implies dv = 2u du     
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              s(t) \amp = \int_4^{4+t^2} \frac{\sqrt{v}}{2} dv 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \frac{v^{\frac{3}{2}}}{3} \Big|_4^{4+t^2} =
              \frac{(4 +t^2)^{\frac{3}{2}}}{3} - \frac{1}{3} 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Then I invert the arclength function.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              s + \frac{1}{3}  \amp = \frac{(4+t^2)^\frac{3}{2}}{3} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              3s + 1 \amp = (4+t^2)^\frac{3}{2}
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              (3s + 1)^{\frac{2}{3}} \amp = 4+t^2
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              (3s + 1)^{\frac{2}{3}} - 4  \amp = t^2
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \sqrt{(3s + 1)^{\frac{2}{3}} - 4} \amp = t
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              t(s) \amp = \sqrt{(3s + 1)^{\frac{2}{3}} - 4} 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Finally, I repalce <m>t</m> with this express to get a
          parametrization in <m>s</m>, which is the parametrization by
          arclength. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp \sqrt{(3s + 1)^{\frac{2}{3}} - 4} 
              \gamma(s) \amp = \amp \left( 
              \left((3s + 1)^{\frac{2}{3}} - 4 \right) 
              \cos \left( \sqrt{(3s + 1)^{\frac{2}{3}} - 4} \right), 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp \amp \amp \left( (3s + 1)^{\frac{2}{3}} - 4 \right) 
              \sin \left( \sqrt{(3s + 1)^{\frac{2}{3}} - 4} \right)
              \right) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Parametrize this curve by arclength. (The function
          <m>s(t)</m> will turn out to be imposible to invert
          algebraically.  You can just leave the inverse implicit.
          Also, the integral is a difficult trig substitution; please
          just ask a computer algebra system for the result of the
          integral.) 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp \gamma(t) = (\ln t, 2t^2 - 1) \amp \amp t
              \in [1, \infty) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          First, I calculate the derivatives of the coordinate
          functions.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp x^\prime = \frac{1}{t} 
              \amp \amp y^\prime = 4t 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Then I calculate the pythagorian combination of these.
          <me>
            \sqrt{\frac{1}{t^2} + 16t^2} = \sqrt{\frac{1 +
            16t^4}{t^2}} = \frac{1}{t} \sqrt{ 1+ 16t^4} 
          </me>
          Then I set up the arclength function, which is the integral
          of this pythagorian combination.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              s(t) \amp = \int_1^t \frac{1}{u} \sqrt{ 1+ 16 u^4} du 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          I asked a computer algebra system for the value of this
          integral. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              s(t) \amp =  \frac{1}{2} \left( \sqrt{1 + 16t^4} -
              \arctanh \left( \sqrt{ 1 + 16t^4 \right) - \sqrt{17} +
              \arctanh (17) \right) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          This is not algebraically invertible. All I can do is call
          the inverse <m>t(s)</m> and replace it implicitly. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \gamma(s) \amp = \left( \ln t(s), 2(t(s))^2 - 1)
              \right) \amp \amp s \in [0,\infty) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Parametrize this curve by arclength. (The function
          <m>s(t)</m> will turn out to be impossible to invert
          algebraically.  You can just leave the inverse implicit.
          Also, the integral is a difficult trig substitution; please
          just ask a computer algebra system for the result of the
          integral.) 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp \gamma(t) = (t^2 - 4t + 1, 2t - 2) \amp \amp t
              \in [0, \infty) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          First, I calculate the derivatives of the coordinate
          functions.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp x^\prime = 2t - 4
              \amp \amp y^\prime = 2
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Then I calculate the pythagorian combination of these.
          <me>
            \sqrt{4t^2 - 16t + 16 + 4} = \sqrt{4t^2 - 16t + 20} = 2
            \sqrt{t^2 - 4t + 5} 
          </me>
          I'm going to complete the square here to make this more
          approachable.
          <me>
            2 \sqrt{t^2 - 4t + 5} = 2 \sqrt{(t-2)^2 + 1}
          </me>
          Then I set up the arclength function, which is the integral
          of this pythagorian combination.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              s(t) \amp = \int_0^t 2 \sqrt{(u-2)^2 + 1} du 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          I can shift using the substitution <m>v = u-2</m>
          <md>
            <mrow>
              s(t) \amp = \int_{-2}^{t-2} 2 \sqrt{v^2 + 1} du 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          This is a trig substitution. I asked a computer algebra for
          the solution.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              s(t) \amp = \frac{1}{2} \left( \sqrt{(t-2)^2 + 1} +
              \arcsinh t - 2 - \sqrt{3} - \arcsinh (-2)} \right)  
            </mrow>
          </md>
          This is not algebraically invertible. All I can do is
          implicitly write <m>t(s)</m> for the inverse. Then I can
          replace <m>t</m> with this <m>t(s)</m> in this curve. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \gamma(s) \amp = \left( (t(s))^2 - 4t(s) + 1, 2t(s) - 2
              \right) \amp \amp t \in [0, \infty) 
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
